{{Image requested|date=December 2011|images of the festival|cat=Nanao City}}

'''Kōda no Himatsuri''' (向田の火祭り) is a {{ill|fire festival|ja|火祭り|12=draft}} and {{ill|Kiriko Festival|ja|能登キリコ祭り|12=draft}} held at {{ill|Iyahime Shrine|ja|伊夜比咩神社|12=draft}} in {{ill|Kōda Town|ja|向田町|12=draft}}, {{ill|Notojima|ja|能登島|12=draft}}, {{ill|Nanao, Ishikawa|ja|七尾市|12=draft}}, {{ill|Ishikawa Prefecture|ja|石川県|12=draft}}. The festival takes place annually on the last Saturday of July and is considered one of the {{ill|Three Great Fire Festivals of Japan|ja|日本三大一覧#祭り|12=draft}}. It is designated as an {{ill|Intangible Folk Cultural Property|ja|無形民俗文化財|12=draft}} of Ishikawa Prefecture.<ref>[http://www.pref.ishikawa.lg.jp/kyoiku/bunkazai/minzoku/k2-3.html 能登島向田の火祭（石川県公式サイト）]（Accessed December 5, 2018）</ref> Alongside the {{ill|Seihaku Festival|ja|青柏祭|12=draft}}, {{ill|Okuma Kabuto Festival|ja|お熊甲祭|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Ishizaki Hōtō Festival|ja|石崎奉燈祭|12=draft}}, it is one of the Four Great Festivals of Nanao.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.city.nanao.lg.jp/kikaku-s/shise/sesaku/1sogokekaku/honpen/documents/kihonkeikaku_1_4_5.pdf|title=Basic Plan Chapter 1: Cultural Sector|publisher=Nanao City|accessdate=August 4, 2024|page=88}}</ref>{{Refnest|group="Note"|Some sources consider the Four Great Festivals of Nanao to be the {{ill|Seihaku Festival|ja|青柏祭|12=draft}}, {{ill|Ishizaki Hōtō Festival|ja|石崎奉燈祭|12=draft}}, {{ill|Nanao Gion Festival|ja|七尾祇園祭|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Nanao Port Festival|ja|七尾港まつり|12=draft}}.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://yamaguchi-ev.com/ishikawa-event/1692/|title=Ishikawa Prefecture Events: May|publisher=Yamaguchi Inc.|accessdate=August 4, 2024}}</ref>}}.

== Overview ==
Around 8:00 PM, a {{ill|mikoshi|ja|神輿|12=draft}} bearing a sacred lantern departs from Iyahime Shrine, accompanied by seven large and small {{ill|kiriko|ja|キリコ|12=draft}} lantern floats. At Sakiyama Plaza, a towering 30-meter pillar torch ({{ill|Taimatsu|ja|松明|12=draft}}) is erected. After circling it seven times, the sacred flame from the mikoshi is transferred to torches held by local residents and visitors, who spin them while circling the pillar torch. At a signal from a flute, the torches are thrown into the pillar torch, which bursts into bright flames. The direction in which the torch collapses predicts the year’s fortune: "abundant harvest" if it falls towards the mountain, and "plentiful catch" if it falls towards the sea.

The festival was designated as an Intangible Folk Cultural Property of Ishikawa Prefecture on {{ill|January 14, 1987|ja|昭和62nd year 1月14日|12=draft}} and included in the national designation of "Intangible Folk Cultural Properties requiring measures for documentation" on {{ill|December 4, 1997|ja|平成9th year 12月4日|12=draft}} as part of the Noto Kiriko Festivals.<ref>[https://bunka.nii.ac.jp/heritages/detail/161401 Cultural Heritage Online (Agency for Cultural Affairs)]（Accessed December 5, 2018）</ref> It was also recognized as part of the {{ill|Japan Heritage|ja|日本遺産|12=draft}} titled "The Light Dancing Peninsula, Noto: The Passion of the Kiriko Festivals" on {{ill|April 24, 2015|ja|平成27th year 4月24日|12=draft}}.<ref>[http://www.bunka.go.jp/seisaku/bunkazai/nihon_isan/ichiran.html List of Recognized Japan Heritage Sites (Agency for Cultural Affairs)]（Accessed December 5, 2018）</ref>.

== Facilities Introducing Kōda no Himatsuri ==
